f their lives and adventures by analyzing archival records of maritime industry, captains' logs, ships' records, and the journals of the sailors themselves, among other artifacts. Much of what is known about this period comes from the writings of Herman Melville, and in this book Melville's whaling novels act as a prism through which relations aboard ships are understood. Drawing on both history and literature, Roving Mariners provides a comprehensive history of Australian Aboriginal whaling and sealing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAboriginal Australians -- Commerce. 0aAboriginal Australians -- Fishing. 0aAboriginal Australians -- History. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxCommerce. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxFishing. 0aAboriginal AustraliansxHistory. 0aSealing -- Australia -- History. 0aSealingzAustraliaxHistory. 0aWhaling -- Australia -- History. 0aWhalingzAustraliaxHistory. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aHistory : History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438444253423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438444253/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles